BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:C_WHcTf-7cBJH5Jgb2gRb
SUMMARY:TADAIMA: I'm Home
DTSTAMP:20260321T221842Z
DTSTART:20260328T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:After more than 80 years\, a treasured collection returns “home
	” to Seattle’s Japanese American community. In 1942 dozens of traditional 
	Boys’ and Girls’ Day dolls were entrusted to Bailey Gatzert Elementary Sch
	ool by Japanese American families facing forced incarceration. Most were n
	ever reclaimed after the war. Artist Miya Sukune uses recent research in M
	OHAI’s collection\, as well as interviews with Japanese American survivors
	 and their descendants\, to create an installation called “Tadaima\,” mean
	ing “I’m home.”\n\nTADAIMA: “I’m Home!” Bringing Seattle’s Girls’ and Boys
	’ Day Dolls Home reconnects the dolls with their traditional role of prote
	cting and blessing children. It invites visitors to celebrate the resilien
	ce\, memory\, and enduring traditions of the Japanese American Community.\
	n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-03-28T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - All Events
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-03-28T00
LOCATION:Museum of History and Industry\, 860 Terry Ave N\, Seattle\, Seatt
	le\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-all
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - All Events
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:moptLUZnh1NPR24diFquN
SUMMARY:Restoration Event | Pioneer Park
DTSTAMP:20260321T221842Z
DTSTART:20260328T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Pioneer Park Clean Up!\n\nJoin us for a Forest Steward led wo r
	k party in Pioneer Park SE. For this work party volunteers will be removi 
	ng ivy that is blanketing the forest floor. Removing ivy helps to increase
	  the biodiversity of park by making room for native plants to sprout up. 
	I f left unchecked\, ivy will grow over our native plants and eventually p
	ull them to the ground. Your help in removing ivy will play a pivotal role
	 i n creating a healthier future for the park!\n\nNo experience necessary\
	, all ages welcome. Please note: we require participants aged 14 and under
	  to volunteer with a parent or guardian at a ratio of 1 adult to 3 kids.\
	n\nWhen: Saturday\, March 28th\, 10am-12pm\n\nWhere: Pioneer Park SE\, a m
	ap will be provided for directions to the specific work site. \n\nWhat to 
	bring : Dress for the weather in clothes you don't mind getting dirty \\(t
	hink: lo ng pants\, boots or sneakers\\). Bring water. Small snacks\, glov
	es\, and tools will be provided.\n\nRegistration: https://volunteersignup.
	org/CWRCR\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/restoration-eve
	nt-pioneer-park/18066420/2026-03-28T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - All Events
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/restoration-event-pioneer
	-park/18066420/2026-03-28T00
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-all
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - All Events
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT2H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ZN2oVpwaEPCeOk8Aq3GZm
SUMMARY:Beyond Mysticism: The Modern Northwest
DTSTAMP:20260321T221842Z
DTSTART:20260328T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:image: Drift No. 2\, 1936\, Malcolm M. Roberts\, American\, 191
	3-1990\, tempera on board\, 25 1/2 x 20 5/8 in.\, Seattle Art Museum\, Eug
	ene Fuller Memorial Collection\, 37.103\, © Malcolm M. Roberts\, photo: Sc
	ott Leen.\n\nInspired by the region’s natural beauty and rapidly changing 
	city\, this exhibition showcases artists who told the raw story of Seattle
	 in the 20th century. By sharing the Pacific Northwest’s perspective throu
	gh trending art styles—including Social Realism\, Surrealism\, and Abstrac
	t Expressionism—these artists offered a unique take on Modernist art and c
	hallenged the “mystic” label ascribed to their works.\n\nSpearheading the 
	movement were local icons Mark Tobey\, Kenneth Callahan\, Guy Anderson\, a
	nd Morris Graves—but the range and breadth of Pacific Northwest art goes b
	eyond the “Big Four” of the Northwest School. Featuring more than 150 piec
	es\, this exhibition showcases works that investigate the complexities of 
	daily life in the region. Whether applying an ecocritical lens or producin
	g dreamy and uncanny visuals\, these artists expressed the duality of the 
	natural world and city life to warn of the environmental and social impact
	s of industrialization.\n\nFrom Malcolm Roberts to Kenjiro Nomura\, learn 
	how Northwest artists applied their regional perspective to broader artist
	ic developments to create a new form of American Modernism.\n\nThe exhibit
	ion is accompanied by a fully illustrated catalogue authored by Theresa Pa
	panikolas\, SAM’s Ann M. Barwick Curator of American Art.\n\nhttps://seato
	day.6amcity.com/events/#/details/beyond-mysticism-the-modern-northwest/183
	08126/2026-03-28T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/beyond-mysticism-the-mode
	rn-northwest/18308126/2026-03-28T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
